body:
# Nixpkgs already has goreleaser

nixpkgs already has a setup for goreleaser, which you can run with nix using `nix shell nixpkgs#goreleaser` (modern flake-enabled CLI), or `nix-shell -p goreleaser` (older syntax, but still current).

The nix search 
https://search.nixos.org/packages?channel=22.11&show=goreleaser&from=0&size=50&sort=relevance&type=packages&query=goreleaser shows that 1.13 is the stable version.

The stable Nix configuration is at https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/blob/nixos-22.11/pkgs/tools/misc/goreleaser/default.nix while the unstable version is bang up to date at v1.16.0 - https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs/blob/master/pkgs/tools/misc/goreleaser/default.nix

# Issues with nixpkgs

The goreleaser Nix maintainers are doing a great job (thanks!) of keeping up to date, but having a central nixpkgs repo has some drawbacks in terms of getting releases merged into the central repo, and also, I often want to update just one tool (like `goreleaser`), not take in all of the downstream updates.

With nixpkgs, I'd often find myself maintaining my own version of something just to use a specific version, e.g. https://github.com/a-h/dotfiles/commit/6363839dca6a226bf3d064a4f70b355d90d7d48d or I'd have to pin a specific commit like the left hand side of this: https://github.com/a-h/dotfiles/commit/ea06709d306e80af920e02b359c5a95827d6e2f4

# How flakes help and how tool makers can help

Some tools are maintaining their own flake.nix files, so that you can use them as overlays. For example the xc tool maintains a flake here: https://github.com/joerdav/xc/blob/main/flake.nix

If I want to use it, I can run `nix shell github:joerdav/xc` and it will pull the latest commit of the repo, execute the build if required and I've got it.

But... I can also update my config to use @joerdav's flake as an overlay: https://github.com/a-h/dotfiles/commit/89ddf6254e911edd1030836d0d29dc534afa5e2a

The `flake.nix` takes in the stable nixos packages, but then I'm overlaying `xc` with the flake. Since @joerdav maintains the flake, I can remove my self-maintained version. Pinning is taken care of by the flake lock file, and because I can specific a specific git tag in the `github:joerdav/xc` input.

```nix
{
  inputs = {
    nixpkgs.url = "nixpkgs/nixos-22.11";
    home-manager = {
      url = "github:nix-community/home-manager";
      inputs.nixpkgs.follows = "nixpkgs";
    };
    xc = {
      url = "github:joerdav/xc";
      inputs.nixpkgs.follows = "nixpkgs";
    };
    darwin = {
      url = "github:lnl7/nix-darwin";
      inputs.nixpkgs.follows = "nixpkgs";
    };
  };

  outputs = inputs@{ self, nixpkgs, darwin, home-manager, xc, ... }:
    let
      pkgs = import nixpkgs {
        overlays = [
          (self: super: {
            xc = xc.packages.aarch64-darwin.xc;
          })
        ];
      };
    in rec {
      homeConfigurations = {
        adrian-linux = home-manager.lib.homeManagerConfiguration {
          system = "x86_64-linux";
          inherit pkgs;
          modules = [ ./.config/nixpkgs/home.nix ];
        };
      };
      darwinConfigurations = {
        adrian-mac = darwin.lib.darwinSystem {
          system = "aarch64-darwin";
          specialArgs = {inherit inputs;};
          inherit pkgs;
          modules = [ ./.config/nixpkgs/darwin-configuration.nix ];
        };
      };
    };
}
```

Since I wanted to use the latest `goreleaser` today, I created a flake for it at https://github.com/a-h/nix-goreleaser for personal use.

If I run `nix shell github:a-h/nix-goreleaser` I get a shell with the latest commit.

If I run `nix run github:a-h/nix-goreleaser`, it runs `goreleaser` from the latest commit of the flake.

Unlike with nixpkgs, I can tag versions, so I have tagged v1.15.2 and v1.16.0. Now I can run `nix shell github:a-h/nix-goreleaser/v1.15.2` to get that version and `nix shell github:a-h/nix-goreleaser/v1.16.0` to get the other.

I think this is pretty cool.

# Binary distribution vs source

There was some discussion in the other issues related to nix support around wanting to ship binaries. As it happens, I didn't bother to look at the existing nixpkgs configuration and jumped straight into making my own, and gave up when the tests failed (due to goreleaser tests expecting to be in a git repo), and didn't notice that the existing nixpkgs configuration dealt with it by setting `doCheck = false;`

So... I made a hacky binary distribution version that really isn't in the spirit of nix, but got me working this morning. FWIW, the existing nixpkgs config works great, and is more appealing than binary distribution to me, but if you want to go that route, my example shows it's possible:

```nix
{ pkgs, stdenv, fetchurl, autoPatchelfHook }:

let
  mapPlatformToName = platform:
    if platform.isDarwin then "Darwin"
    else if platform.isLinux then "Linux"
    else platform.parsed.kernel.name;

  suffixToHash = {
    # Use `print-hashes.sh` to generate the list below
    Linux_x86_64 = "19n5ywhg8gdav611w0iil1drnr4l1ba7akb8andi9fk54h8r70a9";
    Linux_arm64 = "0j28cddj5vvw6ni0hpgzazsn5qmg4pmmm23vqlrw535xvixi40jw";
    Darwin_x86_64="0mfsv7r2gm8zichc3rgfx45ivwfcvw6yjnl19rwmh0damir5c6yr";
    Darwin_arm64 = "1z6na7q4ws1mxbyiimp8vagb0wvfl9pqd4pvcisz62hw7wkza2fr";
  };

  mapPlatformToArchitecture = platform: {
    "x86_64" = "x86_64";
    "aarch64" = "arm64";
  }.${platform.parsed.cpu.name} or (throw "Unsupported CPU ${platform.parsed.cpu.name}");

  version = "v1.16.0";

  mapPlatformToSuffix = platform: "${mapPlatformToName platform}_${mapPlatformToArchitecture platform}";

  suffix = mapPlatformToSuffix stdenv.hostPlatform;
in
stdenv.mkDerivation {
  pname = "goreleaser";
  version = version;
  src = fetchurl {
    url = "https://github.com/goreleaser/goreleaser/releases/download/${version}/goreleaser_${suffix}.tar.gz";
    sha256 = suffixToHash.${suffix} or (throw "Missing hash for suffix ${suffix}");
  };
  sourceRoot = "."; # goreleaser doesn't have a folder in the tar.gz file.
  nativeBuildInputs = if pkgs.stdenv.isLinux
    then [ autoPatchelfHook ]
    else [];
  installPhase = ./install.sh;
  system = builtins.currentSystem;
}
```

# My thoughts

I currently think it would be best to maintain a `flake.nix` file in the `goreleaser` project, much like the https://github.com/joerdav/xc project does. Flakes seem to be the direction of travel, and it will keep the nix ecosystem up to date immediately when a new goreleaser release hits.

Yes, I think that's the way.

I don't think it's very easy to get into Nix, but I never tried to really sit down and learn it methodically. Like, I didn't really try to understand the language properly by building up my understanding of the language alone. I was trying to read examples, and not really understanding what the code was doing for a while. I tend to use IDE autocomplete to discover fields and capabilities, and Nix doesn't really lend itself to that, you've got to use the repl and read the source code to find out what's available.

I use it for my systems, but it's just a tool for me, I don't want to spend too much time on it, I want to build other things.

I think it would be worth getting feedback on my proposal of a way forward from the the listed maintainers of the `goreleaser` Nix package. That's:

@c0deaddict
@endocrimes
@sarcasticadmin
@techknowlogick
@developer-guy
@caarlos0

I'd love to hear your thoughts on this proposal.

okay, fwiw I experimented a bit with this and NUR today... so now you can install goreleaser pro on nix!

for instance, using flake and home manager:


```nix
{
  description = "Home Manager configuration of Carlos Becker";

  inputs = {
    nixpkgs.url = "github:nixos/nixpkgs/nixos-unstable";

    home-manager = {
      url = "github:nix-community/home-manager";
      inputs.nixpkgs.follows = "nixpkgs";
    };

    mkAlias = {
      url = "github:cdmistman/mkAlias";
      inputs.nixpkgs.follows = "nixpkgs";
    };

    nix-index-database = {
      url = "github:Mic92/nix-index-database";
      inputs.nixpkgs.follows = "nixpkgs";
    };

    nur.url = "github:nix-community/NUR";
    caarlos0-nur.url = "github:caarlos0/nur";
  };

  outputs = { nur, caarlos0-nur, home-manager, nix-index-database, ... }@inputs:
    let
      overlays = final: prev: {
        nur = import nur {
          nurpkgs = prev;
          pkgs = prev;
          repoOverrides = { caarlos0 = import caarlos0-nur { pkgs = prev; }; };
        };
        # ... your other overlays
      };
    in {
        "user@host" = home-manager.lib.homeManagerConfiguration {
          pkgs = inputs.nixpkgs.legacyPackages.x86_64-linux;
          extraSpecialArgs = { inherit inputs; };
          modules = [
            ({ config, ... }: {
              config = { nixpkgs.overlays = [ overlays ]; };
            })
            ({ pkgs, ... }: {
              home.packages = [ pkgs.nur.repos.caarlos0.goreleaser-pro ];
            })
          ];
        };
      };
}
```

The source is heavily based on @a-h examples, if you wanna check it out: https://github.com/caarlos0/nur

If you think this is a good approach, we could something that does this automatically into goreleaser...

User would still have to set up their NUR repo, and add their packages to the `default.nix` file... but wouldn't need to change anything on updates.

Another thing to investigate is if we can/its worth it reverse-engineer `nix-prefetch-url`... if not, we can assume the user will have to have it installed.


Thoughts?
